South African Corn Climbs for Third Day, Tracking U.S. Benchmark

-- B y   M k h u l u l i   M a n c o t y w a
-- 
2011-03-01T10:41:36Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-01/south-african-corn-climbs-for-third-day-tracking-u-s-benchmark.html
Corn advanced for a third day in
 South Africa , the continent’s largest producer of the grain,
after prices rose in the U.S., which competes for African export
markets.  White corn for July delivery added 7 rand, or 0.4 percent,
to end trade at 1,652 rand ($237) a metric ton on the  South
African Futures Exchange  in Johannesburg. Meal made from the
grain is the country’s staple food.  Corn futures for May delivery rose 9 cents, or 1.2 percent,
to $7.31 a bushel on the Chicago Board of Trade yesterday, the
highest close for the contract since trading started in June
2009. It gained as much as 0.4 percent in electronic trading
today.  Yellow corn for July delivery gained 22 rand, or 1.3
percent, to 1,703 rand a ton. The grain is used mainly as  animal
feed  in  South Africa .  Wheat for May delivery increased 15 rand, or 0.5 percent,
to 3,191 rand a ton.  The gains or losses for the most active contracts of the
following crops today were as follows. All prices are in rand
and the crops are sold in tons:  To contact the reporter on this story:
